As when a Penal Law is given to compel men to duties to which they were bound before by Law, divine, natural, or human: as, “Whoso slays a man, let him be put to death:” “Whoso exports goods, let him pay the customs, or forfeit the goods:’' these oblige under fault, so that a man does not satisfy his conscience, who submits to the penalty3 he must also obey the Law. But this obligation arises out of the preceding Law, divine in the one case, human in the other.
